<div id="review_3560189498" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3560189498" />
    <a title="Noah Goats" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41735508-noah-goats"><img alt="Noah Goats" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1526489093p2/41735508.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3560189498?book_show_action=true">Sep 25, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Noah Goats" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Noah Goats" href="/user/show/41735508-noah-goats">Noah Goats</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3560189498" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3038150994553327704">In The Anatomy Lesson, Nathan Zuckerman, one of the greatest whiners in American literature, is subjugated by a mysterious pain in the neck that robs him of his ability to write and drives him to something near madness. Of course, Roth being Roth, the one thing that being crippled by pain does not take away from Zuckerman is his ability to fornicate, which he does with a quartet of lovely women of various sorts (he should have watched the episode of Curb Your Enthusiasm where Larry David explain</span>
  <span id="freeText3038150994553327704" style="display:none">In The Anatomy Lesson, Nathan Zuckerman, one of the greatest whiners in American literature, is subjugated by a mysterious pain in the neck that robs him of his ability to write and drives him to something near madness. Of course, Roth being Roth, the one thing that being crippled by pain does not take away from Zuckerman is his ability to fornicate, which he does with a quartet of lovely women of various sorts (he should have watched the episode of Curb Your Enthusiasm where Larry David explains the only two ways a person can injure their neck).<br /><br />In Zuckerman Unbound, Zuckerman loses his father and is left feeling unmoored and liberated by the fact. Like Roth, (because Zuckerman is very much like Roth) Zuckerman had struggled for years to free himself from the tyranny of family and Jewish tradition, and seemed to have it at last. In the Anatomy Lesson he loses his mother as well, and this seems to crush him. The novel is about loss, the struggle for self-identity, coping with celebrity, being Jewish in America, male-female relationships in the era of sexual liberation, and the big betrayer that is the human body. The protagonist is both funny and unlikable. I've always admired Roth's style and I wasn't bored for a moment while reading this.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3038150994553327704" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


